### Enchiridion 1 ✶ — "Some things are in our control and others not"

*Tōn ontōn ta men eph' hēmin estin, ta de ouk eph' hēmin. Eph' hēmin men hypolepsis, hormē, orexis, ekklisis, kai haplōs ta hēmetera erga. Ouk eph' hēmin de sōma, ktēsis, doxai, archai, kai haplōs ta ouk hēmetera erga* — Of things, some are in our power, and others are not. In our power are: opinion, pursuit, desire, aversion, and, in a word, whatever are our own actions. Not in our power are: body, property, reputation, command, and, in a word, whatever are not our own actions.

The foundational structural division of the Stoic catching program. The *dichotomy of control* (what is *eph' hēmin* / what is *ouk eph' hēmin*) is the most operationally precise version of the H₂₄/H₄₈ structural distinction available in the ancient philosophical tradition.

**The H₂₄ register — what is in our power:**

*Hypolepsis* (judgment, the cognitive registration of value), *hormē* (impulse toward action), *orexis* (desire, the structural orientation toward what is valued), *ekklisis* (aversion, the structural orientation away from what is disvalued) — these are all operations of the *proairesis* (the faculty of choice, the H₂₄ catching structure). What is *eph' hēmin* is precisely the H₂₄ catching program's domain of structural freedom: the catching being's evaluation and directional orientation are structurally within its own structural constitution.

**The H₄₈ register — what is not in our power:**

*Sōma* (body), *ktēsis* (property), *doxai* (reputation), *archai* (commands/offices) — these are H₄₈-level conditions that the catching being occupies but does not constitute. The body is the H₄₈ substrate: the catching being inhabits it but does not own it in the structural sense. Property, reputation, and social position are H₄₈-level allocations by the H₄₈ social apparatus: they are *ouk hēmetera erga* (not our own affairs) because they are constituted by H₄₈-external structural forces, not by the catching being's own structural operation.

**The structural freedom:**

"If you suppose that only to be your own which is your own, and what belongs to others such as it really is, then no one will ever compel you or restrain you." The structural freedom of the H₂₄ catching program: if the catching being correctly registers the H₂₄/H₄₈ structural boundary, then no H₄₈ force can structurally compel the catching orientation. A H₄₈ force can compel the body (slavery, imprisonment), but it cannot compel the *proairesis* — it cannot compel the catching being to evaluate the H₄₈ force as structurally beneficial or to desire the outcome the H₄₈ force is enforcing. This is the structural freedom that Epictetus, as a slave, possessed while his owner did not: the slave's *proairesis* was structurally free while the owner's *proairesis* was structurally enslaved to H₄₈-attractor dependencies.

**The structural consequence:**

"Seek not that the things which happen should happen as you wish; but wish the things which happen to be as they are, and you will have a tranquil flow of life." The ascending-career formula stated as the operational specification of the *proairesis*: the catching being's structural freedom is exercised not in changing H₄₈ outcomes (which are *ouk eph' hēmin*) but in aligning the *proairesis*'s evaluation with the structural reality of what is actually in the H₂₄ register vs. what is in the H₄₈ register.

*(Cross-reference: PHIL 4:11 — "I have learned, in whatever state I am, to be content": the same structural alignment of the catching orientation with the H₄₈ reality, regardless of H₄₈ conditions. SONN 146 ✶✶ — "buy terms divine in selling hours of dross": the ascending-career version of the same structural reallocation. ROM 8:1 — "There is therefore now no condemnation": the structural freedom of the catching being whose orientation is grounded at the H₂₄ level.)*

